Save this recipe for my Italian meringue buttercream! I use it to cover and fill all my cakes as I find it’s a much smoother, less sweet alternative to American buttercream. I think it tastes like softserve 🍦 YUM! Recipe below 👇🏽

Ingredients:
2 c granulated sugar
3/4 cup water
3/4 cup egg whites (I always used pasteurized egg whites)
1 lb unsalted butter
4 oz salted butter 
cut all your butter into smaller pieces and bring to room temperature 
1 TBSP really good vanilla (I use Nielsen Massey)

Method:
Make sure your mixing bowl, beaters and pot are all clean and free of oils or your egg whites will not whip up properly.

1. Pour sugar and water in a pot and bring to boil. Do not stir!!! This will encourage the formation of sugar crystals. If crystals start forming on the sides of the pot you can wipe them down with a brush dipped in some water. Insert a candy or probe thermometer and set alarm to 118C. You will eventually bring this sugar mixture up to 120C but I always set the alarm slightly earlier so I can make sure to be ready to remove it from the heat once it’s reached 120C.
2. As the sugar is coming to temperature, beat egg whites in your mixer with the whisk attachment at medium speed until the egg whites begin to form soft peaks.
3. Once the sugar comes to temperature, turn the mixer down to low and slowwwly add the sugar syrup to the egg whites by pouring down the side of the bowl. DO NOT pour into the whisk or else this molten liquid will go flying and you can risk burning yourself! Once all the sugar is added turn the mixer up to medium/high and whisk until stiff glossy peaks form.
4. Switch to paddle attachment and set mixer to low/medium. Add your butter one piece at a time and continue to mix. You are slowly trying to get the butter and meringue to emulsify, which is why at one point you will see everything start to look like cottage cheese. Keep mixing, it will eventually get smooth!
5. Once your buttercream is smooth. Slowly pour in your vanilla and continue to mix.
6. Remove 1 c of buttercream and melt in the microwave. Pour melted buttercream back into mixer and beat until you have soft, smooth buttercream.

Here’s how I use an airbrush to get a realistic finish  on my chicken McNugget cake pops!

The trick is layering shades of orangey brown from light to dark to get a toasty finish. I custom mix my airbrush paints using a variety of gel colours diluted to different strengths with @artisanaccents dilution solution. 

I colour match by testing my colours on a scrap piece of modelling chocolate, and then comparing it to the real nugget until I have just the right shade. It’s a slow and steady process but the Virgo in me is all about getting the details just right👌😂

Airbrush kit: @temptu 
Dilution solution: @artisanaccents

As a child on my days home sick from school, the thing that excited me most was being able to watch all the daytime tv shows that I would otherwise be bingeing if it were not for my parents’ insistence that I learn how to read (the nerve!). One of my favourite daytime personalities was @marilyndenis on CityLine. She was warm and funny, and whether the segment was fashion, home decor or cooking, it always felt like I was learning something alongside Marilyn. Oh how I DREAMED of being part of her studio audience! Fast forward a couple decades and I get an email asking if I would be a GUEST on the @themarilyndenisshow ! 🤯A dream that wasn’t even within the realm of possibilities had come true and I couldn’t believe it. I am forever grateful to have had the chance to meet this ever iconic, talented, funny, intelligent (the list goes on…) woman, who ends her 34 year reign as the queen of Canadian daytime television today. Marilyn, thank you for being my substitute teacher over the years and wishing you all the best on this next chapter. I’m forever a fan, whatever you do. ❤️🇨🇦

Here are 4 tips to help ensure your cakes arrive safely on delivery day!

✨ Hot glue cleats (small cardboard or wooden feet) underneath your cake boards/drums for heavy cakes so you can get your hands under the base more easily without accidentally touching the cake (extra important when your cake is close to the edges of your cake board!)
✨For very tall cakes you can extend the height of your box with additional thin cake boards
✨Always place your cakes in the car on a flat surface with a silicone/rubber mat underneath to prevent sliding
✨Always bring a cake repair kit with you in case there are any fixes or touches required on site! I’ll post another video to show you what I typically include in my repair kit!

📝POP QUIZ! 📝With these three cake decorating essentials, the possibilities are endless!

Read how I use each ingredient below, and see if you can guess which elements on my cake charcuterie board are made of which ingredient. 🚨 And STAY TUNED if you want to learn more cake decorating secrets, because I’ll be making some big announcements soon! 📢🎉🥳

Modeling chocolate: this is my go to ingredient whenever I am creating an edible sculpture. Modeling chocolate behaves just like clay which means you can blend it into itself, an essential feature when trying to hide seams. When it comes to larger decorations, I opt for modeling chocolate because it tastes like white chocolate, and IMHO I’d eat a sizable piece of chocolate over fondant any day.

Gumpaste: a stiffer version of fondant with greater elasticity which means you can roll it out SUPER thin and it maintains its structure. It also dries to a beautiful porcelain hard finish, perfect for edible flower petals that need to be both delicate and strong 

Fondant: sugar paste that feels and acts a lot like playdough! It’s a really great all purpose ingredient that you can use to cover cakes or model figurines.

🍰 To peek or not to peek? Let’s settle the oven debate! 🚫

🙅🏽‍♀️ DON’T OPEN the oven while baking your cake to keep that perfect rise and consistency. Here’s why:
❌ Heat Loss: Opening the oven releases precious heat, leading to uneven baking. 🌡️
❌ Sinking Risk: Sudden temperature drops can cause your cake to collapse. 📉
❌ Extended Bake Time: Frequent peeks add minutes to your baking clock. 🕒

✨ When to CHECK: ✨
1. Use a timer 🕒
2. If you can, resist peeking before 2/3 of the suggested bake time ⏳

This funfetti cake was filled with a strawberry Italian meringue buttercream and strawberry coulis. A touch heavy on the coulis at first 🥴 but after a quick rescue mission it was back in top form. 

I usually try to include up to three components in my cakes to create a balance of flavours and textures:

🍰 a creamy filling like Italian meringue buttercream or chocolate ganache. Besides being delicious, buttercream and ganache hold cake crumbs at bay and create a smooth clean canvas to apply additional fondant or modeling chocolate decorations.
🍰 a fruit coulis or caramel add moisture to the cake and a nice contrast/complement to the flavour of the buttercream/ganache.
🍰Crispearls, cookie crumbs, or even cereal are great for infusing more flavour and texture contrast to the softness of the cake.

Remember, it’s all about BALANCE 😉, so don’t let any one element steal the cake’s spotlight!

🚨This dollar store hack is NOT for you if you actually enjoy the thrill of rummaging through a bin of leaky food colours. 

✨For the rest of us who prefer to save our precious time, money, and sanity, here’s the play by play and why it works:

🍰 I bought several of these bead storage units from the craft section of the dollar store and simply removed the horizontal dividers
🍰I separated all my food colours into categories: liquid, powdered, and metallics and then further organized them by colour inside each container. 

WHY THIS WORKS:
🍰Some brands show the colour only on the side of the label so even if you’ve got all your colours neatly standing in a bin or shelf, you’re looking down on a sea of white caps with no idea what colour is inside. With this method every single colour is clearly visible without even opening the lid!
🍰I use many different brands of colours and there are so many different types of containers, from tubes, to squeeze bottles, to pots… 99% of my colours fit inside these containers regardless of the brand.
🍰THE BIGGEST BONUS for me about this storage solution is that you can stack all the colours on top of each other no matter what shape they are, and store them UPRIGHT. This means NO MORE LEAKS (a major problem particularly with oil-based colours) and no more money wasted on product that is in the bin instead of in your cake!

I have said goodbye to my giant messy food colour bins forever and replaced them with these little containers that sit in my cupboard like a beautiful rainbow library. Let me know if you’re going to try this and be sure to like and follow for more cake hacks, tips and tricks!!

Here’s how I made them:
👻 I added a bit of buttercream to my chocolate fudge cake scraps (my freezer is stocked with them!). I’d say 1 tablespoon of buttercream to 1 cup of cake. Just enough so the cake pop holds together like clay when you squeeze it in your hand.
👻 roll this mixture into a ball and put them in the freezer for an hour or 2 until firm
👻 melt your favourite chocolate in the microwave for 30 seconds at a time, stirring in between until fully melted. I used @callebautchocolate #811 Dark Callets
👻 poke a paper straw into the chocolate and then into your frozen cake ball, then back into the chocolate and  stand them up in a styrofoam block. 
👻 roll out some white fondant and cut with a 4” circle cutter. I used @satin.ice 
👻 drape onto the cake pop then use a small round piping tip to cut out the eyes
